my_mips
=======

A MIPS-I userland emulator. It loads a MIPS little-endian program (either a
flat binary produced with objcopy, or an ELF executable) into an emulated
address space and interprets it instruction by instruction, emulating a
small set of SPIM-compatible syscalls for I/O.


Building
--------

    make            # builds everything (release, debug, asan, tests)
    make release    # optimized build  -> build/bin/my_mips
    make debug      # debug build       -> build/debug/my_mips
    make asan       # AddressSanitizer  -> build/asan/my_mips
    make clean      # remove object files
    make distclean  # remove binaries and generated files

Note: the MIPS target programs under test/ are built with clang
(--target=mipsel-linux-gnu) and linked with the mipsel binutils linker,
because Ubuntu no longer ships a mipsel gcc cross-compiler. See test/c/Makefile.


Usage
-----

    ./build/bin/my_mips [-l] [-d] <program>

    <program>   a MIPS little-endian flat binary (.exe) or ELF executable
    -l          log/trace every executed instruction (pc, raw word, mnemonic)
    -d          drop into the integrated debugger instead of running freely

Example:

    $ mipsel-linux-gnu-as hello.s -o hello.o
    $ mipsel-linux-gnu-objcopy -O binary hello.o hello.exe
    $ ./build/bin/my_mips hello.exe
    Hello World!


How it works
------------

Memory model
    The whole address space is a single mmap'd buffer (see MEM_SIZE in
    include/define.h). The program is loaded at address 0 and execution
    starts at the entry point (pc = 0). The stack pointer ($sp) is
    initialized to the top of memory and grows downward, matching the
    model in the subject.

Registers
    32 general purpose registers plus the special HI/LO pair and PC are
    kept in the global state (struct global). Register $0 is hardwired to
    0. Conventional register names (V0, A0, SP, RA, ...) are defined in
    include/define.h.

Decoding and dispatch
    Each 32-bit instruction is classified as one of the three MIPS formats
    (R, I, J) from its opcode/function fields, then dispatched to a handler:
        exec_register   - R-type (opcode 0): arithmetic, logic, shifts,
                          HI/LO moves, jr/jalr
        exec_immediate  - I-type: immediate arithmetic/logic, branches,
                          loads and stores
        exec_jump       - J-type: j, jal
    Unknown opcodes return an error.

Delay slots
    Branches and jumps execute the instruction in their delay slot before
    transferring control, as required by the MIPS-I architecture.

Syscalls
    The SYSCALL instruction dispatches on $v0 using the SPIM convention.
    Implemented syscalls:
        1  print_int      4  print_string   5  read_int    8  read_string
        10 exit           11 print_char     12 read_char   13 open
        14 read           15 write          16 close       17 exit2
    Following the subject, a trap writes 1 to $k0 on overflow and 0
    otherwise instead of raising a real exception.


Layout
------

    src/         emulator source
    include/     headers
    test/        assembly test programs (.s) and their build
    test/c/      C test program compiled to MIPS and run on the emulator
    docs/        project subject
